[[Orljava]], [[Bosut (river)|Bosut]]\n| tributaries_right  = [[Ljubljanica]], [[Krka (Sava)|Krka]], [[Kupa]], [[Una (Sava)|Una]], [[Vrbas (river)|Vrbas]], [[Ukrina]], [[Bosna (river)|Bosna]], [[Tinja (river)|Tinja]], [[Drina]], [[Kolubara]]\n| extra              = <sup>a</sup> Including {{convert|45|km|abbr=on}} [[Sava Dolinka]] [[headwater]]\n}}\nThe '''Sava''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|s|a\u02d0|v|\u0259}};<ref>[http://www.dictionary.com/browse/sava?s=t \"Sava\" ''Dictionary.com'']</ref> {{IPA-sl|\u02c8s\u00e0\u02d0\u028ba}},<ref>{{cite web|title=Slovenski pravopis 2001: Sava|url=http://bos.zrc-sazu.si/c/SP/neva.exe?name=sp&expression=Sava&hs=1}}</ref> {{IPA-sh|s\u01ce\u02d0\u028ba|lang}},<ref>{{cite web|title=Hrvatski jezi\u010dni portal: Sava|url=http://hjp.novi-liber.hr/index.php?show=search_by_id&id=dlZmWhQ%3D&keyword=Sava}}</ref> {{lang-sr-cyr|\u0421\u0430\u0432\u0430}}) is a [[river]] in [[Central Europe]], a right tributary of the [[Danube]]. It flows through [[Slovenia]], [[Croatia]], along the northern border of [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]], and through [[Serbia]], discharging into the Danube in [[Belgrade]]. Its central part is a [[natural border]] of Bosnia-Herzegovina and Croatia. The Sava forms the northern border of the [[Balkan Peninsula]], and the southern edge of the [[Pannonian Plain]].\n\nThe Sava is {{convert|990|km|abbr=off|0}} long, including the {{convert|45|km|adj=on}} [[Sava Dolinka]] [[headwater]] rising in [[Zelenci]], Slovenia. It is the greatest [[List of tributaries of the Danube|tributary of the Danube]] by volume of water, and second-largest after [[Tisza]] in terms of catchment area ({{convert|97713|km2|abbr=off}}) and length. It drains a significant portion of the [[Dinaric Alps]] region, through the major tributaries of [[Drina]], [[Bosna (river)|Bosna]], [[Kupa]], [[Una (Sava)|Una]], [[Vrbas (river)|Vrbas]], [[Lonja]], [[Kolubara]], [[Bosut (river)|Bosut]] and [[Krka (Sava)|Krka]]. The Sava is one of the longest [[rivers in Europe]] and among a handful of European rivers of that length that do not drain directly into a sea.\n\nThe population in the Sava River basin is estimated at 8,176,000, and it connects three national capitals\u2014[[Ljubljana]], [[Zagreb]] and Belgrade. The Sava is navigable for larger vessels from the confluence of the Kupa River in [[Sisak]], Croatia, approximately two-thirds of its length.\n\nThe name is believed to be derived from the Proto-Indo-European root ''*sewh<sub>1</sub>'' ('to take liquid', whence the English word ''sup'') and the ending ''*eh<sub>2</sub>'', so that it literally means 'that which waters [the ground]'.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://hrcak.srce.hr/23286|title=Stara Europa u Hrvatskoj: ime rijeke Save|last=Udolph|first=J\u00fcrgen|date=28 March 2007|journal=Folia Onomastica Croatica|issue=12/13|accessdate=19 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Sources==\n{{see also|Sava Bohinjka|Sava Dolinka}}\n[[File:Zelenci2.JPG|thumb|left|[[Zelenci]]\u2014spring of [[Sava Dolinka]]]]\n[[File:Sava at Okroglo.jpg|thumb|left|Sava near Okroglo]]\n\nThe Sava River is formed from the [[Sava Dolinka]] and the [[Sava Bohinjka]] [[headwater]]s in northwest [[Slovenia]]. The river's headwater area also encompasses several [[tributary|tributaries]], including the {{convert|52|km|adj=on}} [[Sora (river)|Sora]], the {{convert|27|km|adj=on}} [[Tr\u017ei\u010d Bistrica]] and the {{convert|17|km|adj=on}} [[Radovna (river)|Radovna]] rivers\u2014flowing into the Sava at [[confluence]]s located as far east downstream as [[Medvode]].{{sfn|Vrhovec|Pristov|Ho\u010devar|1996|p=123}}{{sfn|SURS|2002|p=47}}\n\nThe Sava Dolinka rises at the [[Zelenci]] Pools near [[Kranjska Gora]], Slovenia, in a valley separating the [[Julian Alps]] from the [[Karavanke]] [[mountain range]].{{sfn|Carey|Clark|2005|p=50}} The spring is located near the Slovene-[[Italy|Italian]] border at {{convert|833|m|abbr=off}} [[above sea level]],{{sfn|SURS|2002|p=47}}{{sfn|Tockner|Uehlinger|Robinson|2009|loc=chapter 3.9.6.}} in a [[drainage divide]] between the [[Adriatic Sea|Adriatic]] and [[Danube basin]]s. The Sava Dolinka [[Spring (hydrology)|spring]] is fed by [[groundwater]] possibly exhibiting [[River bifurcation|bifurcation]] of source [[karst]] [[aquifer]] to the Sava and [[So\u010da]] basins.{{sfn|Tri\u0161i\u010d|Bat|Polajnar|Pristov|1997|pp=295\u2013298}} [[Nadi\u017ea (creek)|Nadi\u017ea]] creek, a short [[losing stream]] flowing nearby, is the source of Zelenci Pools water.{{sfn|Carey|Clark|2005|p=50}} The Sava Dolinka is considered the Sava's initial,{{sfn|SURS|2002|p=47}} {{convert|45|km|adj=on}} segment.{{sfn|ISRBC|September 2009|p=12}}\n\nThe Sava Bohinjka originates in [[Rib\u010dev Laz]], at the confluence of the [[Jezernica]],{{sfn|Oro\u017een|1901|pp=96}} a short watercourse flowing out from [[Lake Bohinj]] and the [[Mostnica]] River.{{sfn|WFFC|2012}} Some sources define the Jezernica as a part of the Sava Bohinjka, specifying the latter as flowing directly out of the lake,{{sfn|Fallon|2010|p=133}} while another group of sources include [[Sava Bohinjka|Savica]], rising at the southern flank of [[Triglav]] as the {{convert|78|m|adj=on}} [[Savica Falls]],{{sfn|McKelvie|McKelvie|2008|p=111}} downstream from [[Triglav Lakes Valley]], and flowing into the lake, as a part of the Sava Bohinjka.{{sfn|Singleton|1985|p=3}} The watercourse flows {{convert|41|km|abbr=off}}\u2014including the length of the Savica\u2014east to [[Radovljica]],{{sfn|SURS|2002|p=47}} where it discharges into the Sava Dolinka. Downstream from the confluence, the river is referred to as the Sava.{{sfn|Tri\u0161i\u010d|Bat|Polajnar|Pristov|1997|pp=295\u2013298}}\n\n==Course==\n[[File:SLO-Litija5.JPG|thumb|right|Sava at [[Litija]]]]\nThe Sava is located in [[Southeast Europe]], flowing through Slovenia, Croatia, Serbia and along the Bosnia-Herzegovina border. Its total length is {{convert|990|km|abbr=off|0}}, including the {{convert|45|km|adj=on}} Sava Dolinka and the {{convert|945|km|adj=on}} Sava proper. As a right tributary of the [[Danube]], the river belongs to the [[Black Sea]] drainage basin.{{sfn|ISRBC|September 2009|p=113}}{{sfn|Primo\u017ei\u010d|Kobold|Brilly|2008|p=1}} The Sava River is the [[List of tributaries of the Danube|third longest tributary of the Danube]],{{sfn|ISRBC|February 2009}} slightly shorter than the {{convert|966|km|adj=on}} [[Tisza]] and the {{convert|950|km|adj=on|0}} [[Prut]]\u2014the Danube's two longest tributaries\u2014when the Sava Dolinka headwater is excluded from its course.{{sfn|ICPDR}}{{sfn|Bostan|Gheorghe|Dulgheru|Bostan|2011|p=127}} It is also the largest tributary of the Danube by [[Discharge (hydrology)|discharge]].{{sfn|ISRBC|February 2009}} The river course is sometimes used to describe the northern boundary of the [[Balkans]],{{sfn|Todorova|2009|p=30}} and the southern border of the [[Central Europe]].{{sfn|Promitzer|Hermanik|Staudinger|2009|p=10}} Before the [[breakup of Yugoslavia]] in 1991, the river was located completely inside [[SFR Yugoslavia|Yugoslav]] borders and it was the longest river with its entire course within the country.{{sfn|Lampe|2000|p=13}}\n\n===From the source to the Sutla===\nThe Sava Dolinka rises in the Zelenci Pools, west of [[Podkoren]] in the [[Upper Carniola]] region of Slovenia at {{convert|833|m|abbr=off}} above sea level (a.s.l.),{{sfn|SURS|2002|p=47}}{{sfn|Tockner|Uehlinger|Robinson|2009|loc=chapter 3.9.6.}} and flows east, past Kranjska Gora to [[Jesenice, Jesenice|Jesenice]], where it turns southeast. At [[\u017dirovnica, \u017dirovnica|\u017dirovnica]], the river enters the [[Ljubljana Basin]] and encounters the first [[hydroelectric dam]]\u2014[[Moste, \u017dirovnica|Moste]] plant\u2014before proceeding to the east of the glacial [[Lake Bled]] towards Radovljica and confluence of the Sava Bohinjka,{{sfn||HSE (Moste)}} at {{convert|411|m|abbr=off}} a.s.l.{{sfn|SURS|2002|p=47}} Downstream of Radovljica, the Sava proceeds southeast towards [[Kranj]]. Between Kranj and Medvode, its course comprises the [[Lake Trboje]] and the [[Lake Zbilje]] [[reservoir]]s,{{sfn|ISRBC|September 2009|p=53}} built for the [[Mav\u010di\u010de]] and the Medvode power plants.{{sfn|HSE (Mav\u010di\u010de)}}{{sfn|HSE (Medvode)}}\n\n[[File:Saveschlucht zwischen Lubljana und Trbovlje.jpg|thumb|Sava gorge between Ljubljana and Trbovlje]]\n\nThe Sava then flows through the capital of Slovenia, [[Ljubljana]],{{sfn|Municipality of Ljubljana}} where another reservoir is located on the river, adjacent to the [[Tacen Whitewater Course]].{{sfn|ECRR|2006|pp=81\u201383}} There the river course turns east and leaves the Ljubljana Basin via [[Dolsko]],{{sfn|Municipality of Dol pri Ljubljani|2007}} at {{convert|261|m|abbr=off}} a.s.l. (at confluence of the [[Ljubljanica]] and the [[Kamnik Bistrica]]).{{sfn|SURS|2002|p=47}} The course continues through the [[Sava Hills]], where it passes the [[Litija Basin]] with the mining and industrial town of [[Litija]], the [[Central Sava Valley]] with the mining towns of [[Zagorje ob Savi]], [[Trbovlje]], and [[Hrastnik]], turns to the southeast and runs through the [[Lower Sava Valley]] with the towns of [[Rade\u010de]], [[Sevnica]], and [[Kr\u0161ko]]. The course through the Sava Hills forms the boundary of traditional regions of Lower Carniola and [[Styria (Slovenia)|Styria]],{{sfn|Municipality of La\u0161ko}} At Rade\u010de, the [[Vrhovo, Rade\u010de|Vrhovo]] hydroelectric dam reservoir is located.{{sfn|HSE (Vrhovo)}} The latter is site of the [[Kr\u0161ko Nuclear Power Plant]], which uses the Sava River water to dissipate excess heat.{{sfn|Kr\u0161ko NPP}} The easternmost stretch of the Sava River course in Slovenia runs to the south of [[Bre\u017eice]], where it is joined by the Krka, and the river ultimately becomes a border river between Slovenia and [[Croatia]], marking {{convert|4|km|abbr=off}} of their border near confluence of the [[Sutla]] ({{lang-sl|Sotla}}).{{sfn|ISRBC|September 2009|p=170}} At that point, the Sava reaches {{convert|132|m|abbr=off}} a.s.l. after flowing {{convert|221|km|abbr=off}} through Slovenia and along its border.{{sfn|SURS|2002|p=47}}\n\n===From the Sutla to the Una===\n[[File:Medvednica.jpg|thumb|left|Sava in [[Zagreb]], with [[Medvednica]] mountain in the background]]\n[[File:Sava in Zagreb, 13 Feb 2014.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Sava in Zagreb near [[Youth Bridge]] on 13 February 2014 after record rainfall, which, combined with melting snow, expanded the river to three times its normal size, rising to the height of 347&nbsp;cm and reaching the levees. At the time the picture was taken, the water level started subsiding and was at 287&nbsp;cm.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.voda.hr/HV_PrikazVodostaja_EksternaVS8/A3.aspx?postajaID=5&slivID=1 |title=Sliv Save |accessdate=2014-02-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221224022/http://www.voda.hr/HV_PrikazVodostaja_EksternaVS8/A3.aspx?postajaID=5&slivID=1 |archivedate=21 February 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The trees in the water indicate the usual width of the river, around 100&nbsp;m.<ref>Google Earth</ref>]]\nThe westernmost part of the {{convert|562|km|adj=on}} Sava River course in Croatia,{{sfn|Statistical Yearbook of the Republic of Croatia|2015|p=49}} takes the river east, through the western part of the [[Zagreb County]], between [[Samobor]] and [[Zapre\u0161i\u0107]]. The area encompasses forests interspersed by [[marsh]]es and lakes formed in [[gravel pit]]s.{{sfn|Zagreb County Tourist Board}} As the Sava approaches the capital of Croatia, [[Zagreb]], the marshes give way to urban landscape, but there are surviving examples of the gravel pit lakes, such as the [[Jarun]],{{sfn|Ani\u010di\u0107|Treer|1997|p=162}} and the [[Bundek]] within the city.{{sfn|Nacional|22 May 2006}} At the western outskirts of Zagreb, there is the western terminus of the {{convert|32|km|adj=on}} [[Sava-Odra Canal|Sava\u2013Odra flood-relief canal]] connecting the Sava to the [[Odra (Kupa)|Odra]] River plain which is intended to act as [[flood control]] [[retention basin]].{{sfn|\u0160terc|1979|p=97}} The canal has been built in response to the most destructive flooding of the river that occurred in Zagreb in 1964, when one third of the city was flooded and 17 people were killed.{{sfn|Index.hr|26 October 2011}} The city itself marks the western extent of the Sava River basin area especially prone to flooding, spanning from Zagreb to confluence of the river in [[Belgrade]], [[Serbia]].{{sfn|ISRBC|September 2009|p=187}}\n\nEast of Zagreb, the river turns southeast again further through the [[Central Croatia]], to the [[Sisak-Moslavina County]], the city of [[Sisak]], reaching {{convert|91.3|m|abbr=off}} a.s.l. The city of Sisak marks the westernmost extent of the Sava River navigable to larger vessels. Navigation conditions on the river are poor due to limited [[Draft (hull)|draft]] and fairway width, [[meander]]ing of the river, [[Structure gauge|bridge clearance]] restrictions, poor [[Navigation mark|fairway markings]] as well as presence of sunken vessels and other objects, including [[unexploded ordnance]].{{sfn|ISRBC|September 2009|pp=160-161}} The ordnance is left over from various conflicts including the [[World War II]],{{sfn|Nova TV|4 January 2012}} [[Croatian War of Independence]], [[Bosnian War]],{{sfn|tportal.hr|7 July 2011}} and the [[1999 NATO bombing of Yugoslavia]].{{sfn|Index.hr|19 January 2011}} Before reaching confluence of [[Una (Sava)|Una]] at [[Jasenovac, Sisak-Moslavina County|Jasenovac]] and {{convert|86.8|m|abbr=off}} a.s.l,{{sfn|ISRBC|2011|p=37}} the Sava River traces [[Lonjsko polje Nature Park]],{{sfn|Lonjsko Polje NP (a)}} encompassing marshes frequently flooded by the Sava and its tributaries in the area.{{sfn|Lonjsko Polje NP (b)}}\n\n===From the Una to the Drina===\n[[File:Fluss Save Slavonski Brod.JPG|thumb|right|Sava seen from [[Slavonski Brod]], the bridge in the background links the city to [[Bosanski Brod, Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosanski Brod]] via a [[river island]].{{sfn|Nadilo|2000|p=183}}]]\nDownstream of confluence of the Una River, the Sava is once again tracing an international border\u2014between Croatia and [[Bosnia-Herzegovina]]. Its meandering course runs generally eastwards along [[Bosanska Gradi\u0161ka, Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosanska Gradi\u0161ka]], and [[Slavonski Brod]] to [[\u017dupanja]], where it turns south to [[Br\u010dko]]. There, the river resumes its predominantly eastward course towards [[Sremska Ra\u010da]] and confluence of the [[Drina]] River. The right bank of the Sava, in this segment of its course, belongs to Bosnia-Herzegovina (with Bosnia's all three administrative entities, [[Republika Srpska]], [[Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina]] and the [[Br\u010dko District]], having gateway to the river), while the opposite bank belongs to Croatia and its Sisak-Moslavina, [[Brod-Posavina County|Brod-Posavina]] and [[Vukovar-Srijem County|Vukovar-Srijem]] counties, except in the area of [[Jamena]] and further downstream\u2014which belongs to Serbia and the province of [[Vojvodina]]. No cities in this segment of the course span the river as it represents an international frontier, but there are adjacent settlements located in two different countries, divided by the Sava. Those include Bosanska Gradi\u0161ka, Bosanski Brod and Br\u010dko in Bosnia-Herzegovina and [[Stara Gradi\u0161ka]], Slavonski Brod and [[Gunja, Croatia|Gunja]] in Croatia opposite them.\n\nThe {{convert|337.2|km|adj=on}} segment between the Una and the Drina confluences, marking corresponding to the entire length of the Sava flowing along the border of Bosnia-Herzegovina, exhibits small change of elevation\u2014from {{convert|86.8|m|abbr=off}} a.s.l at Jasenovac to {{convert|76.6|m|abbr=off}} a.s.l. at Br\u010dko [[Stream gauge|gauges]], over {{convert|287.5|km|abbr=off}} of the river between them.{{sfn|ISRBC|2011|p=69}} The entire course of the river downstream from Zagreb flows down 0.4\u2030 slope on average, significantly less steep than the course in Slovenia, where the average slope exceeds 0.7\u2030\u2014resulting in the Sava's meandering course running through a wide plain bordered by [[wetland]]s.{{sfn|Tockner|Uehlinger|Robinson|2009|loc=chapter 3.9.6.}}\n\n===From the Drina to the Danube===\n[[File:N\u00e1ndorfeh\u00e9rv\u00e1r - 2014.10.21 (15).JPG|thumb|Sava and the Danube at Belgrade]]\n[[File:Luis-Filipe-Gaspar-Belgrado-Servia.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|left|Sava and the historical center of [[Belgrade]].]] \nDownstream from confluence of the Drina, the Sava River changes its eastward course to northeast, until it reaches [[Sremska Mitrovica]], from where it flows to the southeast and then south to [[\u0160abac]], before finally turning east towards Belgrade. Most of the river's course in Serbia represents a border between province of Vojvodina, on the left bank, and [[Central Serbia]], on the right bank. Exceptions to that are in area around Sremska Mitrovica, where both banks are in Vojvodina, and downstream of [[Progar]] suburb of Belgrade where both banks are in Central Serbia. The river meanders and forms wetlands in there as well\u2014the most significant wetland among them centering on [[Obedska bara]] [[oxbow lake]].{{sfn|ISRBC|September 2009|p=12}} The Sava River forms several large [[River island|islands]] in this segment of the course, with the largest among them\u2014{{convert|800|ha|adj=on}} [[Ada Ciganlija]] in Belgrade\u2014connected to the right bank by a pair of artificial [[embankment dam]]s forming [[Lake Sava]] since 1967.{{sfn|ISRBC|2011|p=103}}{{sfn|JP Ada Ciganlija}}\n\nThe Sava discharges into the Danube, after reaching {{convert|68.3|m|abbr=off}} a.s.l. as its right tributary at the [[Great War Island]] off the easternmost tip of [[Syrmia]] in Belgrade, {{convert|1169.9|km|abbr=off}} away from the Danube's confluence and the Black Sea.{{sfn|ISRBC|2011|p=109}}\n\n===Settlements===\nPopulation in the Sava River basin is estimated at 8,176,000, and it includes four capitals\u2014Belgrade, Ljubljana, [[Sarajevo]] and Zagreb. All of them, except Sarajevo, are also located directly on the river banks and represent the three largest settlements found along the Sava River course.{{sfn|ISRBC|September 2009|p=146}} Belgrade, located at the confluence of the river, is the largest city in the basin with urban population of 1,135,502. Ten municipalities where the city is situated have combined population of 1,283,783 as suburban settlements are added, while the Belgrade [[metropolitan area]] encompasses population of 1,639,121.{{sfn|RZS|2011|p=19}} Zagreb is the second largest city on the river, comprising population of 688,163 living in the city itself, and 802,588 in the city-administered area.{{sfn|Croatian Census|2011}} Together with the Zagreb County, largely corresponding to various definitions of the city's metropolitan area,{{sfn|Ba\u0161i\u0107|2005|pp=63-64}} it has a combined population of 1,110,517.{{sfn|Croatian Census|2011}} Ljubljana is the third-largest city on the banks of the Sava, encompassing population of 258,873 living in the city itself and 265,881 in the city-governed area.{{sfn|SURS Census \u2013 Naselja|p=L|2002}}{{sfn|SURS Census \u2013 Ob\u010dine|2007}}\n\nThe largest city in Bosnia-Herzegovina situated on the Sava River course is Br\u010dko, whose urban population is estimated at 40,000.{{sfn|CoM BiH|2003|p=13}} Other cities along the river, with populations of 20,000 and larger, are Slavonski Brod (53,473), \u0160abac (52,822), Sremska Mitrovica (37,586), Kranj (35,587),{{sfn|SURS Census \u2013 Naselja|p=K|2007}} Sisak (33,049),{{sfn|Croatian Census|2011}} [[Obrenovac]] (24,568),{{sfn|RZS|2011|p=21}} and Bosanska Gradi\u0161ka (est. 20,000).{{sfn|Municipality of Gradi\u0161ka}}\n\n{|class=\"infobox\" style=\"text-align:center; width:97%; margin-right:10px; font-size:90%\"\n!align=center colspan=11|The most populous urban areas along the Sava River\n|-\n!rowspan=23 width:150|<br/>\n[[File:Belgrade iz balona.jpg|135px|Belgrade]]<br/>[[Belgrade]]<br/>\n[[File:Trg bana Jelacica Zagreb 30102012 2 roberta f.jpg|135x135px]]<br/>[[Zagreb]]<br/>\n!align=center style=\"background:#f5f5f5;\"|Rank\n!align=center style=\"background:#f5f5f5;\"|City\n!align=center style=\"background:#f5f5f5;\"|Country\n!align=center style=\"background:#f5f5f5;\"|Urban population\n!align=center style=\"background:#f5f5f5;\"|Municipal population\n!rowspan=23 width:150|\n[[File:Ljubljana from the Castle.JPG|135px|Ljubljana]]<br/>[[Ljubljana]]<br/>\n[[File:Korso slavonski brod.jpg|border|135px|Slavonski Brod]]<br/>[[Slavonski Brod]]<br/>\n|-\n|align=center style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|1||align=left|[[Belgrade]]||[[Serbia]]||1,233,350||1,659,440\n|-\n|align=center style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|2||align=left|[[Zagreb]]||[[Croatia]]||802,588||1,110,517\n|-\n|align=center style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|3||align=left|[[Ljubljana]]||[[Slovenia]]||258,873||265,881\n|-\n|align=center style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|4||align=left|[[Slavonski Brod]]||Croatia||53,473||59,507\n|-\n|align=center style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|5||align=left|[[\u0160abac]]||Serbia||52,822||115,347\n|-\n|align=center style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|6||align=left|[[Br\u010dko (town)|Br\u010dko]]||[[Bosnia-Herzegovina]]||40,000||85,000\n|-\n|align=center style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|7||align=left|[[Sremska Mitrovica]]||Serbia||37,586||79,773\n|-\n|align=center style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|8||align=left|[[Kranj]]||Slovenia||35,587||51,225\n|-\n|align=center style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|9||align=left|[[Sisak]]||Croatia||33,322||47,768\n|-\n|align=center style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\"|10||align=left|[[Obrenovac]]||Serbia||24,568||71,419\n|-\n|colspan=\"5\" align=center style=\"background:#f5f5f5;\"|<small>Sources: Statistical Office of the Republic of Serbia 2011 Census;{{sfn|RZS|2011|pp=19, 21}} [[Croatian Bureau of Statistics]], 2011 Census;{{sfn|Croatian Census|2011}} [[Statistical Office of the Republic of Slovenia]], 2002 Census;{{sfn|SURS Census \u2013 Naselja|2007}} [[Council of Ministers of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]{{sfn|CoM BiH|2003|p=13}}</small>\n|}\n{{clear}}\n\n==Watershed==\n[[File:Aerial photo of Br\u010dko Bridge in 1996.jpg|thumb|right|Br\u010dko Bridge between [[Br\u010dko (town)|Br\u010dko]] and [[Gunja, Croatia|Gunja]] in 1996. [[Bosnian War|Wartime]] damage was repaired in 2000.{{sfn|HRT|2000}}{{sfn|The Talon|22 March 1996|pp=1, 12}}]]\nThe Sava River basin covers a total area of {{convert|97713.2|km2|abbr=off}} making it the second largest Danube tributary catchment by area size, surpassed only by the Tisza basin,{{sfn|Tockner|Uehlinger|Robinson|2009|loc=chapter 3.9.6.}} and it encompasses 12% of the Danube basin, draining into the Black Sea. The Sava represents the third longest tributary of the Danube and its largest tributary by discharge.{{sfn|ISRBC|February 2009}} The catchment area borders the remainder of the Danube basin to the north and east, and the Adriatic Sea basin to the west and south. The river basin generally consists of parts of Bosnia-Herzegovina, Croatia, [[Montenegro]], Serbia and Slovenia, with a very small part of the catchment area belonging to [[Albania]]. Topography of the basin varies significantly. Upstream portion of the basin is more rugged than downstream one, but asymmetry of the basin topography is particularly apparent when comparing right and left bank areas\u2014the former dominated by the [[Alps]] and the [[Dinarides]] reaching elevations in excess of {{convert|2000|m|abbr=off}} a.s.l, while the latter is dominated by the [[Pannonian Plain]]. The mean elevation of the basin is {{convert|545|m|abbr=off}} a.s.l.{{sfn|ISRBC|September 2009|pp=5-8}}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! Country !! Sava basin area !! Share of national<br/>territory in the basin !! Share of the Sava basin\n|-\n| [[Slovenia]] || align=right|{{convert|11734.8|km2|abbr=on}} || align=center|52.8% || align=center|12.01%\n|-\n| [[Croatia]] || align=right|{{convert|25373.5|km2|abbr=on}} || align=center|45.2% || align=center|25.97%\n|-\n| [[Bosnia-Herzegovina]] || align=right|{{convert|38349.1|km2|abbr=on}} || align=center|75.8% || align=center|39.25%\n|-\n| [[Serbia]] || align=right|{{convert|15147.0|km2|abbr=on}} || align=center|17.4% || align=center|15.50%\n|-\n| [[Montenegro]] || align=right|{{convert|6929.8|km2|abbr=on}} || align=center|49.6% || align=center|7.09%\n|-\n| [[Albania]] || align=right|{{convert|179.0|km2|abbr=on}} || align=center|0.59% || align=center|0.18%\n|-\n| colspan=4|Source: [[International Sava River Basin Commission]];{{sfn|ISRBC|September 2009|p=6}}\n|}\n\n===Major tributaries===\n[[File:Sava Drina Confluence.JPG|thumb|right|The confluence of the Sava and [[Drina]]]]\nThe most important tributaries of the Sava River found in its upper basin are characterized by relatively steep grades of flow, high flow velocities and [[rapid]]s. Those are left tributaries: the [[Kokra]], the Kamnik Bistrica and the [[Savinja]]; and right tributaries: the Sora, the Ljubljanica and the [[Krka (Sava)]]. Further downstream larger rivers empty into the Sava, as the right bank of the basin grows steadily. Right tributaries in this lower segment of the basin start as fast flowing courses, only to slow down as they enter the [[Pannonian Basin]]. They include the [[Kupa]], the Una, the [[Vrbas (river)|Vrbas]], the [[Ukrina]], the [[Bosna (river)|Bosna]], the [[Brka]], the Tinja, the Drina and the [[Kolubara]]. Left tributaries in the lower segment drain plains consequently exhibiting less steep course grades, lower flow rates and meandering. They include the Sutla, the [[Krapina (river)|Krapina]], the [[Lonja]], the [[Ilova River (Croatia)|Ilova]], the [[Orljava]] and the [[Bosut (river)|Bosut]].{{sfn|ISRBC|September 2009|pp=12-13}}\n\nThe {{convert|346|km|adj=on}} Drina is the largest tributary of the Sava, flowing in Bosnia-Herzegovina and along border of the country and Serbia. It is formed by the headwaters of the [[Tara (Drina)|Tara]] and the [[Piva (river)|Piva]] at the border of Bosnia-Herzegovina and Montenegro, near [[\u0160\u0107epan Polje]]. Its {{convert|20319.9|km2|adj=on}} catchment extends across parts of four countries\u2014reaching as far south as Albania. The Bosna and the Kupa river basins are the second and third largest catchments of the Sava tributaries, each surpassing {{convert|10000|km2|abbr=off}} in size.{{sfn|ISRBC|September 2009|pp=12-13}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\" style=\"background:none; cellspacing=2px; text-align:left; font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! colspan=9|List of major tributaries of the Sava River\n|-\n! colspan=3|Left bank !! style=\"width:85px;\" rowspan=2|Catchment area !! style=\"width:85px;\" rowspan=2|Length !! style=\"width:100px;\" rowspan=2|Confluence !! colspan=3|Right bank\n|-\n! Country !! Region/County !! Tributary !! Tributary !! Region/County !! Country\n|-\n| rowspan=3|[[Slovenia]] || [[Central Slovenia Statistical Region|Central Slovenia]] || || align=right|{{convert|1860.0|km2|abbr=on}} || align=right|{{convert|41.0|km|abbr=on}} || align=center|{{coord|46.075553|N|14.641857|E|display=inline|type:river|name=Ljubljanica}} || [[Ljubljanica]] || Central Slovenia || rowspan=4|Slovenia\n|-\n| [[Savinja Statistical Region|Savinja]] || [[Savinja]] || align=right|{{convert|1849.0|km2|abbr=on}} || align=right|{{convert|93.9|km|abbr=on}} || align=center|{{coord|46.085733|N|15.178471|E|display=inline|type:river|name=Savinja}} || || Savinja\n|-\n| [[Lower Sava Statistical Region|Lower Sava]] || || align=right|{{convert|2247.0|km2|abbr=on}} || align=right|{{convert|94.6|km|abbr=on}} || align=center|{{coord|45.893772|N|15.601187|E|display=inline|type:river|name=Krka}} || [[Krka (Sava)|Krka]] || rowspan=2|Lower Sava\n|-\n| rowspan=11|[[Croatia]] || rowspan=2|[[Zagreb County|Zagreb]] || [[Sutla]] || align=right|{{convert|584.3|km2|abbr=on}} || align=right|{{convert|88.6|km|abbr=on}} || align=center|{{coord|45.864015|N|15.684614|E|display=inline|type:river|name=Sutla}} || rowspan=2|\n|-\n| [[Krapina (river)|Krapina]] || align=right|{{convert|1237.0|km2|abbr=on}} || align=right|{{convert|66.9|km|abbr=on}} || align=center|{{coord|45.827244|N|15.823359|E|display=inline|type:river|name=Krapina}} || Zagreb || rowspan=4|Croatia\n|-\n| rowspan=4|[[Sisak-Moslavina County|Sisak-Moslavina]] || || align=right|{{convert|10225.6|km2|abbr=on}} || align=right|{{convert|297.4|km|abbr=on}} || align=center|{{coord|45.460793|N|16.398296|E|display=inline|type:river|name=Kupa}} || [[Kupa]] || rowspan=3|Sisak-Moslavina\n|-\n| [[Lonja]] || align=right|{{convert|4259.0|km2|abbr=on}} || align=right|{{convert|49.1|km|abbr=on}} || align=center|{{coord|45.363846|N|16.753807|E|display=inline|type:river|name=Lonja}} || rowspan=2|\n|-\n| [[Ilova River (Croatia)|Ilova-Trebe\u017e]] || align=right|{{convert|1796.0|km2|abbr=on}} || align=right|{{convert|104.6|km|abbr=on}} || align=center|{{coord|45.348707|N|16.772604|E|display=inline|type:river|name=Ilova}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2| || align=right|{{convert|9828.9|km2|abbr=on}} || align=right|{{convert|214.6|km|abbr=on}} || align=center|{{coord|45.27096|N|16.918516|E|display=inline|type:river|name=Una}} || [[Una (Sava)|Una]] || colspan=2|[[List of international border rivers|Border river]] at the confluence\n|-\n| rowspan=4|[[Brod-Posavina County|Brod-Posavina]] || align=right|{{convert|6273.8|km2|abbr=on}} || align=right|{{convert|249.7|km|abbr=on}} || align=center|{{coord|45.107939|N|17.51328|E|display=inline|type:river|name=Vrbas}} || [[Vrbas (river)|Vrbas]] || rowspan=3|[[Republika Srpska]] || rowspan=5|[[Bosnia-Herzegovina]]\n|-\n| [[Orljava]] || align=right|{{convert|1618.0|km2|abbr=on}} || align=right|{{convert|87.6|km|abbr=on}} || align=center|{{coord|45.106773|N|17.724724|E|display=inline|type:river|name=Orljava}} ||\n|-\n| rowspan=4| || align=right|{{convert|1504.0|km2|abbr=on}} || align=right|{{convert|80.7|km|abbr=on}} || align=center|{{coord|45.088702|N|17.936854|E|display=inline|type:river|name=Ukrina}} || [[Ukrina]]\n|-\n| align=right|{{convert|10809.8|km2|abbr=on}} || align=right|{{convert|281.6|km|abbr=on}} || align=center|{{coord|45.066792|N|18.466043|E|display=inline|type:river|name=Bosna}} || [[Bosna (river)|Bosna]] || [[Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n|-\n| [[Vukovar-Srijem County|Vukovar-Srijem]] || align=right|{{convert|904.0|km2|abbr=on}} || align=right|{{convert|99.4|km|abbr=on}} || align=center|{{coord|44.927893|N|18.75628|E|display=inline|type:river|name=Tinja}} || [[Tinja (river)|Tinja]] || [[Br\u010dko District]]\n|-\n| rowspan=3|[[Serbia]] || rowspan=2|[[Vojvodina]] || align=right|{{convert|20319.9|km2|abbr=on}} || align=right|{{convert|346.0|km|abbr=on}} || align=center|{{coord|44.891968|N|19.355249|E|display=inline|type:river|name=Drina}} || [[Drina]] || colspan=2|Border river at the confluence\n|-\n| [[Bosut (river)|Bosut]] || align=right|{{convert|2943.1|km2|abbr=on}} || align=right|{{convert|186.0|km|abbr=on}} || align=center|{{coord|44.941443|N|19.369583|E|display=inline|type:river|name=Bosut}} || || Vojvodina || rowspan=2|Serbia\n|-\n| [[Central Serbia]] || || align=right|{{convert|3638.4|km2|abbr=on}} || align=right|{{convert|86.6|km|abbr=on}} || align=center|{{coord|44.662152|N|20.248532|E|display=inline|type:river|name=Kolubara}} || [[Kolubara]] || Central Serbia\n|-\n| colspan=9|Notes: Country/region/county of location of confluence with Sava corresponding to tributary bank side;<br>The list includes rivers with catchment areas greater than {{convert|900|km2|abbr=off}}, with addition of Sutla.<br/>Source: [[International Sava River Basin Commission]];{{sfn|ISRBC|September 2009|pp=13-14}}\n|}\n\n==Hydrology==\n[[File:Smlednik-Zbilje.JPG|thumb|left|Lake Zbilje upstream from [[Medvode]]]]\nThe average annual [[Discharge (hydrology)|flow rate]] of the Sava River at Radovljica, immediately downstream of the Sava Dolinka and the Sava Bohinjka confluence, stands at {{convert|44.9|m3|abbr=off}} per second.{{sfn|Oikos|2008|p=20}} Downstream of the Krka confluence the average flow rate reaches {{convert|317|m3|abbr=off}} per second,{{sfn|Mayer|1996|p=31}} gradually increasing as tributaries discharge along the course\u2014{{convert|340|m3|abbr=off}} per second downstream of the Sutla, {{convert|880|m3|abbr=off}} per second following discharge of the Kupa and the Una, {{convert|990|m3|abbr=off}} per second downstream of the Vrbas confluence, {{convert|1180|m3|abbr=off}} per second after the Bosna river empties into the Sava,{{sfn|Mayer|1996|p=32}} and finally of {{convert|1564|m3|abbr=off}} per second at confluence of the Sava in Belgrade.{{sfn|ISRBC|February 2009}} The highest flow rate of {{convert|6007|m3|abbr=off}} per second was recorded by Slavonski  \u0160amac [[gauging station]] in May 2014.{{sfn|Tuti\u0161|2014|p=3}}\n\nSeven out of eight largest reservoirs in the Sava River basin are located in the Drina catchment, the largest among them being the {{convert|0.88|km3|adj=on}} Lake Piva on the eponymous river in Montenegro, created after construction of [[Mratinje Dam]]. Overall, there are 22 reservoirs holding more than {{convert|5000000|m3|abbr=off}} of water in the basin, with only four of them situated directly on the Sava, including one on the Sava Dolinka. Most of the reservoirs are used primarily, or even exclusively, for [[electricity generation]], but they are also used as supply of [[drinking water]], [[industrial water]] source, for [[irrigation]] and [[food production]].{{sfn|ISRBC|September 2009|p=53}}\n\nGroundwater is a very important resource in the Sava River basin, generally used for public water supply of potable water, as a source of water for industrial use, but also as the mainstay of [[aquatic ecosystem]]s. There are 41 identified significant groundwater bodies in the Sava River basin of basin-wide importance,{{sfn|ISRBC|November 2011 (a)|p=3}} ranging in area size from {{convert|97|to|5186|km2|abbr=off}}, as well as numerous minor ground water bodies. Even though most of them are [[transboundary waters]], eleven are considered to be largely located in Slovenia, fourteen in Croatia, seven in Bosnia-Herzegovina, five in Serbia and four in Montenegro.{{sfn|ISRBC|November 2011 (a)|pp=5-6}}\n\n==Geology==\nThe course of the Sava River runs through several diverse [[geological unit]]s and [[Orography|orographic regions]]. The uppermost course of the river and its headwaters in the Karavanke area, is situated in the [[Southern Alps (geology)|Southern Alps]], tracing the Sava [[Fault (geology)|Fault]]&mdash;itself running parallel to the [[Periadriatic Seam]]. [[Mesozoic]] and [[Upper Triassic]] rocks are exposed in the region.{{sfn|Placer|2008|p=207}} The Ljubljana Basin represents the boundary of the Southern Alps and the Dinarides.{{sfn|Placer|2008|p=209}} Valleys of the Sava Dolinka and the Sava Bohinjka are [[glacial valley]]s, carved out by the Sava Dolinka and Bohinj [[glacier]]s advancing down Karavanke range to vicinity of present-day Radovljica. In the [[late Pleistocene]], [[Bohinj Glacier]] was the largest glacier in the territory of present-day Slovenia, up to {{convert|900|m|abbr=off}} thick.{{sfn|Bavec|Verbi\u010d|2001|p=385}}{{sfn|Stepi\u0161nik|2012|pp=300\u2013303}} Sava Folds, southeast and east of the Ljubljana Basin are thought of as a part of the Dinarides,{{sfn|Placer|2008|p=206}} separating the Ljubljana and [[Kr\u0161ko Basin]]s,{{sfn|Placer|2008|p=207}} and forming the Sava Hills.{{sfn|Topole|2003|p=53}} The east&ndash;west oriented folds are younger than the [[Miocene]] and the folding is considered to had taken place in the [[Pliocene]] and the [[Quaternary]], but it is possible that the tectonic activity continues in the present day.{{sfn|Topole|2003|p=46}} The Sava Folds largely exhibit [[Paleozoic]] and [[Triassic]] rocks,{{sfn|Kolar-Jurkov\u0161ek|Jurkov\u0161ek|2012|p=324}} and [[clastic sediment]]s.{{sfn|Ramov\u0161|Srema\u0107|Kulenovi\u0107|1987|p=398}}\n\nThe lower course of the Sava River is located in the Pannonian Basin&mdash;first reached by the Sava River in the Kr\u0161ko Basin on the western rim of the Pannonian Basin.{{sfn|Placer|2008|p=208}} The Pannonian Basin took shape through Miocenian thinning and [[subsidence]] of crust structures formed during Late Paleozoic [[Variscan orogeny]]. The Paleozoic and Mesozoic structures are visible in [[Papuk]] and other Slavonian mountains. The processes also led to the formation of a [[Stratovolcano|stratovolcanic]] chain in the basin 17\u201312&nbsp;[[Mya (unit)|Mya]] (million years ago) and intensified subsidence observed until 5&nbsp;Mya as well as [[flood basalt]]s about 7.5&nbsp;Mya. Contemporary uplift of the [[Carpathian Mountains]] prevented water flowing to the Black Sea, and the [[Pannonian Sea]] formed in the basin. Sediments were transported to the basin from uplifting Carpathian and Dinaric mountains, with particularly deep fluvial sediments being deposited in the [[Pleistocene]] during the uplift of the [[Transdanubian Mountains]].{{sfn|Haas|2012|pp=14\u201318}} Ultimately, up to {{convert|3000|m|abbr=off}} of the sediment was deposited in the basin, and the Pannonian sea eventually drained through the [[Iron Gate (Danube)|Iron Gate]] gorge.{{sfn|Hilbers|2011|p=16}} In the southern Pannonian Basin, the [[Neogene]] to Quaternary sediment depth is normally lower, averaging {{convert|500|to|1500|m|abbr=off}}, except in central parts of depressions formed by [[subduction]]. A subduction zone formed in the present-day Sava River valley, and approximately {{convert|4000|m|abbr=off}} deep sediments were deposited in the Slavonia-Syrmia depression and {{convert|5500|m|abbr=off}} in the Sava depression.{{sfn|Safti\u0107|Veli\u0107|Sztan\u00f3|Juh\u00e1sz|2003|p=108}} The results of those processes are large [[plain]]s in the Sava River valley and the Kupa River valley. The plains are interspersed by the [[Horst (geology)|horst]] and [[graben]] structures, believed to have broken the Pannonian Sea surface as [[Pannonian island mountains|islands]],{{sfn|Malvi\u0107|Veli\u0107|2011|p=221}} which became watershed between [[Drava]] and Sava River basins extending along [[Ivan\u0161\u010dica]]\u2013[[Kalnik (mountain)|Kalnik]]\u2013[[Bilogora]]\u2013Papuk mountain chain.{{sfn|Hrvatske vode|loc=section 2.1}} The Papuk Mountain is flanked by the [[Krndija]] and the [[Dilj]] Hills on the eastern rim of the [[Po\u017eega Valley]]. The Bilogora, Papuk and Krndija Mountains consist mostly of Paleozoic rocks which are 300\u2013350&nbsp;million years old, while the Dilj consists of much more recent Neogene rocks, 2\u201318&nbsp;million years old.{{sfn|Pami\u0107|Radoni\u0107|Pavi\u0107|2003|p=6}} Further east of the chain, the watershed runs through the [[\u0110akovo]]\u2013[[Vinkovci]] and [[Vukovar]] Plateau.{{sfn|Ba\u010dani|\u0160parica|Veli\u0107|1999|p=149}} The [[loess]] plateau, extending eastward from Dilj and representing the watershed between the [[Vuka (river)|Vuka]] and Bosut rivers, gradually rises to the [[Fru\u0161ka Gora]] south of Ilok.{{sfn|Vukovar-Syrmia County|2006|p=6}}\n\n==Economy==\n\n===Electric power generation===\nThere are 18&nbsp;hydroelectric power plants with power generation capacity exceeding 10&nbsp;[[Megawatt]]s in the Sava River basin. In Slovenia, most of them are located on the Sava itself. In other countries, the hydroelectric power plants are situated on its tributaries. Total power generation capacity of the 18&nbsp;power plants, and additional smaller plants largely found in Slovenia, amounts to 41,542&nbsp;Megawatts, and their annual production capacity stands at 2,497&nbsp;[[Gigawatt-hour]]s. Approximately {{convert|3.3|km3|abbr=off}} of water per year in the river's basin is used to cool thermoelectric and nuclear power plants. Power plant cooling represents the main type of use of the Sava River waters.{{sfn|ISRBC|December 2010|p=25}}\n\n{{As of|2012|October}}, there are six existing hydroelectric power plants built along the Sava River. Upstream of Ljubljana there are Moste, Mav\u010di\u010de and Medvode power plants, while Vrhovo, [[Bo\u0161tanj]] and [[Blanca, Sevnica|Blanca]] are located downstream of the capital. There is one additional plant under construction near Kr\u0161ko. The Kr\u0161ko hydroelectric power plant, as well as two additional plants planned on the Sava River course downstream of Ljubljana\u2014Bre\u017eice and Mokrice\u2014should be completed by 2018. The power plants downstream of Ljubljana, except Vrhovo, are developed as a chain of five Slovenia's Lower Sava Valley plants since 2002.{{sfn|ISRBC|December 2010|p=15}}{{sfn||HESS (Bo\u0161tanj)}} They will have production capacity of 2,000&nbsp;Gigawatt-hours per year and 570&nbsp;Megawatts of [[installed capacity]]. Completion of the five power plants is expected to cost 700&nbsp;million [[Euro]]s. There are also plans for construction of ten new powerplants in the middle Sava valley HE Suhadol, HE Trbovlje, HE Renke, HE Ponovice, HE Kresnice, HE Jevnica, HE Zalog, HE \u0160entjakob, HE Je\u017eica and HE Tacen. Croatia is planning construction of four hydroelectric power plants on the Sava River in Zagreb area. The four plants\u2014[[Podsused \u2013 Vrap\u010de|Podsused]], Pre\u010dko, Zagreb and [[Drenje Brdove\u010dko|Drenje]]\u2014are scheduled to be completed by 2021 at a cost of 800&nbsp;million Euros. The four power plants will have installed capacity of 122&nbsp;Megawatts and annual production capacity of 610&nbsp;Gigawatt-hours.{{sfn|Jalu\u0161i\u0107|2011|p=9}}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! Hydroelectric power plant !! Location !! [[Installed capacity]] !! Annual production capacity\n|-\n| Moste || [[Moste, \u017dirovnica|Moste]], [[Slovenia]] || align=right|21&nbsp;MW || align=right|56&nbsp;GWh\n|-\n| Mav\u010di\u010de || [[Mav\u010di\u010de]], Slovenia || align=right|38&nbsp;MW || align=right|62&nbsp;GWh\n|-\n| Medvode || [[Medvode]], Slovenia || align=right|25&nbsp;MW || align=right|72&nbsp;GWh\n|-\n| Vrhovo || [[Vrhovo, Rade\u010de|Vrhovo]], Slovenia || align=right|34.2&nbsp;MW || align=right|116&nbsp;GWh\n|-\n| Bo\u0161tanj || [[Bo\u0161tanj]], Slovenia || align=right|36&nbsp;MW || align=right|115&nbsp;GWh\n|-\n| Blanca || [[Blanca, Sevnica|Blanca]], Slovenia || align=right|42&nbsp;MW || align=right|144&nbsp;GWh\n|-\n| colspan=4|Sources: Savske Elektrarne Ljubljana,{{sfn|Savske Elektrarne Ljubljana}} Hidroelektrarne na spodnji Savi.{{sfn|HESS (Projekti)}}\n|}\n\n===Water supply and food production===\nUse of water for public [[water supply]] in the Sava River basin is estimated at {{convert|783000000|m3|abbr=off}} per year, and another {{convert|289000000|m3|abbr=off}} of water per year is used for industrial production purposes. Use of water for [[agriculture]] in the Sava River basin is relatively high, but most of it is applied in non-consumptive uses, such as [[fish farming]]. Use of water for irrigation is relatively low, estimated at {{convert|30000000|m3|abbr=off}} per year.{{sfn|ISRBC|December 2010|p=25}} [[Commercial fishing]] on the Sava River is in decline since the middle of the 20th century. In 1978, there were only 97&nbsp;commercial fishermen there, while [[recreational fishing]] became dominant.{{sfn|Habekovi\u0107|Homen|Fa\u0161ai\u0107|1990|p=9}} The decline became more rapid during the wars in Croatia and Bosnia-Herzegovina, reducing quantity of fish caught in the river to approximately one third of the pre-war catches which ranged from {{convert|719|to|988|t|abbr=off}} between 1979 and 1990.{{sfn|Habekovi\u0107|Safner|Ani\u010di\u0107|Treer|1997|p=99}} The [[International Sava River Basin Commission]] (ISRBC), a cooperative body established by Bosnia-Herzegovina, Croatia, Slovenia and [[Serbia and Montenegro]] in 2005,{{sfn|ISRBC History}} is tasked with establishment of sustainable management of surface water and groundwater resources in the Sava River basin.{{sfn|ISRBC Mission}}\n\n===Navigation and ports===\nThe Sava is navigable to larger vessels for {{convert|593.8|km|abbr=off}} between its confluence with the Danube in Belgrade, Serbia and Galdovo Bridge in [[Sisak, Croatia]], {{convert|2.8|km|abbr=off}} upstream from confluence of Sava and Kupa rivers.{{sfn|ISRBC|2011|p=27}} The confluence marks the westernmost point of the river course designated as a Class IV international [[waterway]] in compliance with the [[United Nations Economic Commission for Europe]]'s European Agreement on Main Inland Waterways of International Importance (AGN).{{sfn|MMATI|2008|p=19}} The classification means that the river course between Sisak and Belgrade is navigable to ships of the maximum length of {{convert|80|to|85|m|abbr=off}}, the maximum beam of {{convert|9.5|m|abbr=off}}, the maximum draught of {{convert|2.5|m|abbr=off}} and tonnage up to {{convert|1500|t|abbr=off}}.{{sfn|UNECE|1996|p=84}} The Sava River downstream of Sisak, is designated as European waterway E&nbsp;80-12, branching off from the E&nbsp;80 waterway spanning the Danube and [[Le Havre]] via the [[Rhine]].{{sfn|UNECE|1996|p=16}} The largest ports on the Sava River are Br\u010dko and \u0160amac in Bosnia-Herzegovina,{{sfn|BMG}} Sisak and Slavonski Brod in Croatia,{{sfn|MMATI|2008|p=18}} and \u0160abac and Sremska Mitrovica in Serbia.{{sfn|Danube Strategy in Serbia}}\n\n{{As of|2008}}, {{convert|24.5|km|abbr=off}} of the river course between [[Slavonski \u0160amac]] and [[Oprisavci]], as well as additional {{convert|219.8|km|abbr=off}} between Slavonski Brod and Sisak, are considered by [[Ministry of Maritime Affairs, Transport and Infrastructure (Croatia)|Croatia's Ministry of Maritime Affairs, Transport and Infrastructure]] to fail the Class IV criteria, permitting navigation of vessels up to {{convert|1000|t|abbr=off}} only, complying with the AGN's Category III.{{sfn|MMATI|2008|p=19}} The Slavonski \u0160amac\u2013Oprisavci section is especially troublesome for navigation as it offers {{convert|250|cm|abbr=off}} draught in less than 50% of an average hydrological year, causing navigation to cease each summer. Similar interruptions are less frequent elsewhere on the river, occurring 30&nbsp;days a year on average upstream from Oprisavci, and even more rarely downstream from Slavonski \u0160amac.{{sfn|MMATI|2010|loc=section 1.1.3.}}\n\nThe restricted draft and fairway is compounded with meandering of the river's course\u2014limiting length of vessels\u2014and low bridge clearance. Further problems are incurred through poor transport infrastructure along the route, including poor navigation markings, and presence of sunken vessels and unexploded [[munitions]].{{sfn|ISRBC|September 2009|pp=160-161}} Navigation along further {{convert|68|km|abbr=off}} of the river upstream to [[Rugvica]] near Zagreb is possible for vessels with [[tonnage]] below {{convert|1000|t|abbr=off}}, and the section of the river belongs to the AGN's Category II. There are plans for restoration of the Category IV compliant waterway downstream of Sisak and betterment of navigation infrastructure between Sisak and Rugvica,{{sfn|MMATI|2008|p=35}} as well as upgrading of the waterway between Br\u010dko and Belgrade to Category Va, matching that of the Danube, with uninterrupted navigation through the year. The plan is planned to be supported by the [[European Union]] and {{as of|2012|October|lc=yes}}, an agreement to implement the plan was signed by Bosnia-Herzegovina and Croatia, while Serbia is invited to join the project. The plan aims to increase safety and volume of river transport, which declined by about 70% since the breakup of Yugoslavia, largely because of poor maintenance of the route.{{sfn|Al Jazeera Balkans|22 April 2012}} The ISRBC is tasked with establishment of an international regime of navigation on the river since 2005.{{sfn|ISRBC Mission}}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! Country !! Port !! Annual cargo !! Year\n|-\n| rowspan=2|[[Croatia]] || [[Sisak]] || align=right|139,899&nbsp;t || align=center|2007{{sfn|MMATI|2008|p=52}}\n|-\n| [[Slavonski Brod]] || align=right|139,364&nbsp;t || align=center|2007{{sfn|MMATI|2008|p=52}}\n|-\n| [[Serbia]] || [[Sremska Mitrovica]] || align=right|295,551&nbsp;t || align=center|2009{{sfn|Danube Strategy in Serbia}}\n|}\n\n===Road, rail and pipeline transport===\nThe Sava River valley is also a route for road and rail traffic. The river valley routes are a part of the [[Pan-European Corridor X]], and forming junctions with [[Pan-European Corridors]] V, Vb, [[Pan-European Corridor Vc|Vc]], Xa and Xb in area of Ljubljana (V), Zagreb (Vb, Xa), Slavonski \u0160amac (Vc), and Belgrade (Xb).{{sfn|EU|9 September 2002}} The motorways forming the Pan-European Corridor X in the area\u2014[[A2 motorway (Slovenia)|Slovenia's A2]], [[A3 (Croatia)|Croatia's A3]] and [[A1 (Serbia)|Serbia's A1]] motorways\u2014represent a part of [[European route E70]] [[Bordeaux]]\u2013[[Turin]]\u2013Ljubljana\u2013Zagreb\u2013Belgrade\u2013[[Bucharest]],{{sfn|ECOSOC|2002|pp=11-12}} and the [[European route E61]] [[Villach]]\u2013Ljubljana\u2013[[Trieste]]\u2013[[Rijeka]].{{sfn|ECOSOC|2002|p=17}} A largely [[double track]] railroad with a [[railway electrification system]] is also a part of the Corridor X.{{sfn|Brnjac|Abramovi\u0107|Maslari\u0107|2010|p=303}} The railroad was a part of the [[Orient Express|Simplon-Orient-Express]] and Direct-Orient-Express routes.<ref>{{Britannica|432308|Orient-Express}}</ref> The navigable river course between Belgrade and Galdovo north of Sisak is spanned by 25&nbsp;bridges.{{sfn|ISRBC Bridges|2011|p=24}} The Sava River valley east of Sisak is also used as a route for the [[Jadranski naftovod]], a [[crude oil]] pipeline. The system connects the [[Port of Rijeka]] oil terminal to [[Oil refinery|oil refineries]] in Rijeka and Sisak, to Bosanski Brod in Bosnia-Herzegovina, as well as [[Novi Sad]] and [[Pan\u010devo]] in Serbia.{{sfn|JANAF}}\n\n==Environmental issues==\n===Pollution===\nThe main pressure on the Sava River basin environment is generated by activities of urban population in the basin.{{sfn|ISRBC|November 2011 (b)|p=38}} Even though nearly all population centres generating pollution above 10,000&nbsp;[[population equivalent]] (PE) have some sort of [[sewage treatment]] in place, less than a quarter of them are adequate.{{sfn|ISRBC|November 2011 (b)|p=41}} Wastewater from 86% of Sava River basin settlements, generating more than 2,000&nbsp;PE, goes untreated. Pollution levels vary along the river. The best conditions in terms of the wastewater treatment are found in Slovenia, although the existing facilities are inadequate.{{sfn|ISRBC|November 2011 (b)|p=42}} \n\nIn Serbia, on the other hand, 68% of population centres have no wastewater treatment facilities at all.{{sfn|ISRBC|November 2011 (b)|p=41}} Population centres exceeding 2,000&nbsp;PE directly discharge into the Sava River basin's surface waters 11,112&nbsp;tonnes of [[nitrogen]] and 2,642&nbsp;tonnes of [[phosphorus]].{{sfn|ISRBC|November 2011 (b)|p=50}} \n\nAgriculture is another significant source of the Sava River basin surface water pollution, specifically through [[livestock]] [[manure]] production. It is estimated that the nutrient pollution levels generated by manure production equal 32,394&nbsp;tonnes of nitrogen and 3,784&nbsp;tonnes of phosphorus per year.{{sfn|ISRBC|November 2011 (b)|p=68}} As a consequence, the Sava River is microbiologically polluted in areas affected by the nutrient pollution. One such part of the river is the lowermost part of its course between \u0160abac and Belgrade, where acceptable freshwater bacterial counts are exceeded.{{sfn|Vukovi\u0107|Markovi\u0107|Radenkovi\u0107|Vukovi\u0107|2011|p=13}}\n\nLevels of industrial pollution vary significantly throughout the basin. In 2007, significant sources of industrial pollution were identified in Slovenia, Bosnia and Herzegovina, and Serbia.{{sfn|ISRBC|November 2011 (b)|p=66}} Levels of lead, cadmium and arsenic measured in the Sava River at Zagreb in 2003 did not exceed permitted concentrations, but measured levels of [[Mercury (element)|mercury]] exceeded permitted levels in four out of 216 samples.{{sfn|Bo\u0161nir|Puntari\u0107|\u0160kes|Klari\u0107|2003|p=34}} Levels of [[heavy metals]], specifically zinc, copper, lead and cadmium, measured in sediments in the Sava River near Belgrade were assessed as representing little to no risk,{{dubious|date=April 2016}} and the conclusion drawn was that in order to \"reduce the existing bacterial contamination of the Sava River it is necessary to control faecal discharge near cities like Belgrade.\" {{sfn|Vukovi\u0107|Markovi\u0107|Radenkovi\u0107|Vukovi\u0107|2011|p=14}} The two countries (Croatia and Montenegro) with greatest direct access to the Adriatic showed by far the least polluted basin surface waters, although other factors, such as demography, agricultural/environmental development and, especially, investment (internal and external), play a role.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=10|Hazardous substances load from significant industrial pollution of the Sava River basin surface waters in 2007\n|-\n! Country !! [[Arsenic]] !! [[Cadmium]] !! [[Chromium]] !! [[Copper]] !! [[Mercury (element)|Mercury]] !! [[Nickel]] !! [[Lead]] !! [[Zinc]] !! [[Phenols]]\n|-\n| [[Slovenia]] || align=right|115 || align=right|0.03 || align=right|83 || align=right|142 || align=right|0.51 || align=right|582 || align=right|75 || align=right|7,656 || align=right|104\n|-\n| [[Croatia]] || align=right|N/A || align=right|N/A || align=right|N/A || align=right|N/A || align=right|0.02 <!--{{sfn|Bo\u0161nir|Puntari\u0107|\u0160kes|Klari\u0107|2003|p=34}}--> || align=right|0.04 || align=right|0.02 || align=right|N/A || align=right|N/A\n|-\n| [[Bosnia-Herzegovina]] || align=right|N/A || align=right|N/A || align=right|1,380 || align=right|983 || align=right|N/A || align=right|21 || align=right|13,629 || align=right|1,656 || align=right|N/A\n|-\n| [[Serbia]] || align=right|2,010 || align=right|N/A || align=right|N/A || align=right|N/A || align=right|N/A || align=right|N/A || align=right|N/A || align=right|1,223 || align=right|2,038\n|-\n| [[Montenegro]] || align=right|N/A || align=right|N/A || align=right|N/A || align=right|N/A || align=right|N/A || align=right|N/A || align=right|246 || align=right|1 || align=right|N/A\n|-\n| colspan=10|Source: [[International Sava River Basin Commission]];{{sfn|ISRBC|November 2011 (b)|p=66}} N/A - data not available\n|}\n\n===Protected areas===\nThe Sava River basin is very significant because of its [[biological diversity]], and it contains large [[alluvial]] wetlands and lowland forests. This led to designation of six protected areas under provisions of the [[Ramsar Convention]] by the countries in the basin. Those are [[Lake Cerknica]] in Slovenia, [[Lonjsko Polje]] and [[Crna Mlaka]] in Croatia, [[Lake Barda\u010da]] in Bosnia-Herzegovina, and Obedska and [[Zasavica (bog)|Zasavica]] bogs in Serbia.{{sfn|ISRBC|December 2010|p=13}}\n\n==Sport and recreation==\n[[File:Tacen Whitewater Course 2.jpg|thumb|The [[Tacen Whitewater Course]] in Ljubljana, Slovenia]]\nThere are several sports and recreational grounds located on the river course or gravel pit and artificial lakes adjacent to the Sava. Tacen Whitewater Course, located on the right bank of the Sava in [[Tacen]] suburb of Ljubljana, was built as a permanent [[kayaking]] course in 1948.{{sfn|Canoe Federation of Slovenia (a)}} It hosts a major international competition almost every year, examples being the [[ICF Canoe Slalom World Championships]] in [[1955 ICF Canoe Slalom World Championships|1955]], [[1991 ICF Canoe Slalom World Championships|1991]],{{sfn|Canoe Federation of Slovenia (b)}} and [[2010 ICF Canoe Slalom World Championships|2010]].{{sfn|Sinfo|October 2010|p=35}} In Zagreb, Jarun complex of lakes along the river course offers a range of facilities for swimming, water sports and cycling.{{sfn|Zagreb Holding}} The island of Ada Ciganlija in Belgrade is the major recreational zone of the city, gathering as much as 100,000 visitors daily in summer months.{{sfn|Politika|14 July 2008}}{{sfn|Press|2 July 2012}}\n\nThe Sava River is the site of several [[regatta]]s. Those include the International Sava Tour [[Rowing (sport)|rowing]] regatta taking place between Zagreb and Br\u010dko,{{sfn|Vasi\u0107|Mandi\u0107|Nedeljkov|2011|p=103}} and the Belgrade Regatta ([[Sailing (sport)|sailing]] regatta).{{sfn|24 sata|8 August 2011}}\n\nThe river is also the site of the [[\u0160abac Swimming Marathon]]&mdash;an [[open water swimming]] competition, running on an {{convert|18.8|km|adj=on}} course between the village of [[Jarak]] and the city of \u0160abac in Serbia. The competition is held annually since 1970, and was included in [[FINA]] international calendar from 1984 to 2012.{{sfn|\u0160abac Marathon|2013}}\n\nRecreational and [[sport fishing]] is a popular activity along the Sava River course.{{sfn|Habekovi\u0107|Homen|Fa\u0161ai\u0107|1990|p=9}} There is a {{convert|700|m|abbr=off}} long sport fishing competition ground near [[Hoteme\u017e]], Slovenia.{{sfn|Slovenian Tourist Board}}\n\n==Tradition==\nEven though the name ''Sava'' became very common among [[Slavs]], especially as a personal name (either male or female) and has a \"Slavic tone\", the river's name has pre-[[Slavic languages|Slavic]] [[Celtic languages|Celtic]] and [[Latin|Roman]] origins;{{sfn|\u0160a\u0161el Kos|2009|p=46}} [[Strabo]] writes in ''Geographica'' 4.6.10 (composed between 20 BCE and 20 CE) of the River ''Sa\u00fcs'',<ref>\n{{cite book\n| last1 = Strabo\n| author-link1 = Strabo\n| editor1-last = Jones\n| editor1-first = H. L.\n| editor2-last = Thayer\n| editor2-first = Bill\n| title = Geographica\n|section=Book IV Chapter 6\n|section-url = http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/4F*.html\n| series = Loeb Classical Library\n| publisher = Harvard University Press\n|date=1917\u20131932\n| access-date = 2016-08-21\n| quote = After the Iapodes comes Segestica [Sisak], a city in the plain, past which flows the River Sa\u00fcs, which empties into the Ister [Danube]. \n}}\n</ref>\nand the Romans used the name ''Savus''. Another name, used for the Sava in entirety or its lower part by Strabo, is ''Noarus''.{{sfn|\u0160a\u0161el Kos|2009|pp=42-43}}\n\nWorship of various river gods in the area dates to the [[Late Bronze Age]],{{sfn|Rendi\u0107-Mio\u010devi\u0107|2012|p=300}} when the first settlements were founded along the Sava River.{{sfn|Vasi\u0107|Mandi\u0107|Nedeljkov|2011|p=78}} [[Taurisci]] associated their [[river god]]dess [[Adsullata]] with the ''Savus''.{{sfn|\u0160a\u0161el Kos|2009|p=46}}{{sfn|Rendi\u0107-Mio\u010devi\u0107|2012|p=300}} Altars or inscriptions dedicated to the river-god Savus have been found at a number of locations along the river course, including at the Zelenci Pools where the Sava Dolinka rises, and a number of [[Roman Empire|Roman]] settlements and [[castra]] built along the Via Pannonia, the [[Roman road]] running from [[Aquileia]] to the Danube.{{sfn|Deluka|Drag\u010devi\u0107|Rukavina|2003|p=739}} The settlements include [[Emona]], [[Andautonia]] and [[Siscia]] (near modern-day Ljubljana, [[Velika Gorica]] and Sisak respectively) upstream of the Kupa River confluence, and [[Marsonia]], itself built atop a [[prehistory|prehistoric]] settlement,{{sfn|Buzov|2011|p=367}} [[Cibalae]], [[Sirmium]] and [[Singidunum]] (in modern-day Slavonski Brod, Vinkovci, Sremska Mitrovica and Belgrade) downstream of the Kupa.{{sfn|Buzov|2011|p=369}} Besides the altar found at the Zelenci Pools, inscriptions and sites dedicated to Savus have been found in remains of Emona,{{sfn|\u0160a\u0161el Kos|2009|p=43}} Andautonia and Siscia.{{sfn|Rendi\u0107-Mio\u010devi\u0107|2012|p=294}} Several years after 1751 completion of the [[Robba Fountain]] in Ljubljana, the three male figures sculpted as parts of the fountain were identified{{by whom?|date=August 2016}} as statues of the river gods of Sava, Krka and Ljubljanica. In the early 20th century, the fountain was named the Fountain of Three [[Carniola]]n Rivers.{{sfn|National Gallery of Slovenia}}\n\nThe [[Romantic poetry|Romantic]] poet [[France Pre\u0161eren]] wrote ''[[The Baptism on the Savica]]'' ({{lang-sl|Krst pri Savici|links=no}}), the [[Slovenes|Slovene]] [[national epic]], in 1835. The poem, referring in its title to a headwater of the Sava River, helped to inspire the design of the [[coat of arms of Slovenia]] of 1991:\n\n[[File:Coat of arms of Slovenia.svg|90px]]\n\nHowever, the two wavy lines at the base of the [[blazon]] officially represent rivers of Slovenia and the Adriatic Sea rather than the Savica or the Sava specifically.{{sfn|GCO|June 2011|p=9}}\n\nThe Sava River also appears symbolically in the coat of arms of the former [[Kingdom of Slavonia]]: \n\n[[File:HRV Slavonia COA.svg|90px]]\n\nThe design, approved by the [[Vladislaus II of Bohemia and Hungary]] in 1496, incorporates two [[Bar (heraldry)|bars]] symbolising the Sava and the Drava rivers tracing the borders of the kingdom. The design inspired the arms of several present-day [[counties of Croatia]] in the region of [[Slavonia]] and itself forms a part of the [[coat of arms of Croatia]].{{sfn|Brun\u010di\u0107|2003|p=44}} The poem ''Horvatska domovina'', written by [[Antun Mihanovi\u0107]] in 1835 as a national symbol of Croatia,  also refers to the Sava River. Modified lyrics of the poem later became the [[Croatian anthem]].{{sfn|MVPEI}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[International Commission for the Protection of the Danube River]]\n* [[Posavina]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist|20em}}\n\n==References==\n;Books\n{{refbegin|2}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Jv4uA1lHezEC|title=Quaternary Glaciations \u2013 Extent and Chronology: A Closer Look, Volume 4|chapter=Glacial History of Slovenia|first1=Milo\u0161|last1=Bavec|first2=Toma\u017e|last2=Verbi\u010d|editor1-first=J.|editor1-last=Ehlers|ed